# Mobile-portable styles

All CSS and styling decisions must work on small screens and touch devices, not only desktop.

## Layout & sizing

- Prefer `rem` / `em` over `px` for typography, spacing, and min-heights so layouts scale with user font settings.
- Do **not** use percentage heights (`min-height: 10%`) unless every ancestor has an explicit height.
- Avoid `100vw` for full-width bars; use `width: 100%` or `max-width: 100%` to prevent horizontal overflow from scrollbars.
- Use `min-height` in `rem` (e.g. `3rem`–`3.5rem`) for nav/header bars—not `vh` or `%`—unless the design intentionally depends on viewport height.
- Use `flex-wrap`, `gap`, and `minmax()` in grids so content reflows on narrow screens.

## Touch & readability

- Interactive targets (links, buttons, nav items) should be at least **44×44px** effective tap area (`padding` + `min-height` count).
- Keep body text readable: avoid font sizes below `0.875rem` for primary content on mobile.

## Responsive patterns

- Add `@media (max-width: 40rem)` (or `48rem`) overrides when desktop layouts would crowd or overflow.
- Reduce `gap`, `padding`, and heading `font-size` on small breakpoints rather than only shrinking width.
- Stack horizontal flex rows vertically on mobile when needed (`flex-direction: column`).

## Safe areas

- Use `env(safe-area-inset-*)` with `max()` for padding on full-bleed headers/nav on notched phones.

## Project conventions

- Reuse design tokens from `src/constants.css` (`--color-*`, `--font-size-*`, glows) instead of hardcoded one-off values.
- Colocate styles in component `.css` files; keep selectors scoped to the component.

## Examples

```css
/* ❌ BAD — breaks on mobile */
.navbar {
  min-width: 100vw;
  min-height: 10%;
}

/* ✅ GOOD */
.navbar {
  width: 100%;
  min-height: 3.5rem;
  padding-block: 0.75rem;
  padding-inline: max(1rem, env(safe-area-inset-right));
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 0.75rem;
}

@media (max-width: 40rem) {
  .navbar {
    min-height: 3rem;
    justify-content: center;
  }
}
```
